<h1>Problem 2278 - 2025 LMAO, P3 of 6, G</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 8</h2>
<p>Let \(ABC\) be an acute triangle with orthocenter \(H\). Let \(M\) be the midpoint of \(BC\), and \(K\) be the intersection of the tangents from \(B\) and \(C\) to the circumcircle of \(ABC\). Denote by \(\Omega\) the circle centered at \(H\) and tangent to line \(AM\).</p>
<p>Suppose \(AK\) intersects \(\Omega\) at two distinct points \(X\), \(Y\).
Lines \(BX\) and \(CY\) meet at \(P\), while lines \(BY\) and \(CX\) meet at \(Q\). Prove that either \(P\) or \(Q\) lies on \(\Omega\).</p>
